<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Burma </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Returns From Nonaligned Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegation Returns From Nonaligned Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0406153994 Rangoon Radio Burma in Burmese 1330 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0406153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rangoon Radio Burma </F>
<F P=105>  Burmese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A Myanmar [Burmese] delegation led by Foreign 
Affairs Minister U Ohn Gyaw returned to Yangon [Rangoon] tonight 
after having attended the 11th foreign ministers' meeting of the 
Nonaligned Movement held in Cairo, Egypt from 31 May to 3 June. 
  The minister and the delegation were welcomed at Yangon 
airport by Lieutenant General Khin Nyunt, secretary-1 of the 
State Law and Order Restoration Council; Lt. Gen. Myo Nyunt, 
minister of religious affairs; Lt. Gen. Kyaw Ba, minister of 
hotels and tourism; U Nyunt Swe, deputy minister of foreign 
affairs; Muhammad Hasan Ghanim, Egyptian ambassador to Myanmar; 
Mohamed Sanusi, Indonesian ambassador to Myanmar; responsible 
personnel from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and family 
members. 
  Major General Kyaw Than, shadow leader of the Myanmar 
delegation, commander of the Central Military Command, and 
chairman of the Mandalay Division Law and Order Restoration 
Council; U Khin Maung Win, deputy director general of the 
Ministry of Foreign Ministry; and U Thaung Tun, director of the 
Ministry of Foreign Ministry, also returned to Yangon with the 
minister. 
  In Cairo, Egyptian President Husni Mubarak received U Ohn 
Gyaw, leader of the Myanmar delegation and minister of foreign 
affairs. Minister U Ohn Gyaw also had a friendly exchange of 
views on bilateral relationships, the Nonaligned Movement, and 
other mutual interests with foreign ministers from Egypt, Cuba, 
Thailand, South Africa, Brunei, Bangladesh, Vietnam, 
Philippines, and Malaysia and the Lao and Italian deputy foreign 
ministers, who were leaders of their delegations. 

</TEXT>

