<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   FUNCINPEC General Reportedly Killed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FUNCINPEC General Reportedly Killed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0306131594 (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia in Cambodian 2330 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0306131594 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia </F>

<F P=105>  Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] It was reported that Nhoek Bunchhai, the 
self-appointed general, the highest ranking commander of the 
FUNCINPEC [National United Front for an Independent, Neutral, 
Peaceful, and Cooperative Cambodia] group, and Prince 
Ranariddh's most able man, died in Samraong District of Oddar 
Meanchey Province on 31 May. 
  What was the cause of Nhoek Bunchhai's death, which members 
of the group have tried hard to hide? 
  The people who often travel in and out of Samraong District 
said that there are two stories concerning Nhoek Bunchhai's 
death. 
  1. As Nhoek Bunchhai went from Samraong to inspect the 
battlefield at Tonle Sar on Route 69, his armored personnel 
carrier ran over a land mine near Tonle Sar. He was killed in 
the explosion. 
  2. When Nhoek Bunchhai was on his way to inspect the 
battlefield along Route 69 west of Samraong, some forcibly 
recruited Para [former non-communist forces] soldiers from 
Prince Ranariddh's group lobbed a grenade into his armored car. 
Nhoek Bunchhai was then killed at the same time as five other 
colonels were killed or wounded. 
  These Para soldiers lobbed the grenade because, on the one 
hand, they were angry with Nhoek Bunchhai and other commanders 
who had sent their subordinates to forcibly recruit them and 
send them out to fight on the battlefield while they were busily 
striving to grow rice to be ready for the coming rainy season. 
This has caused them and their families to face famine and 
untold misery. Moreover, when these soldiers were sent to the 
battlefield, their commanders took liberties with their wives 
and children at home. 
  To the Para soldiers, this is a matter of life and death. 
[passage omitted]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

