<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Companies Sign Agreements With Turkmenistan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Companies Sign Agreements With Turkmenistan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0306133694 Jakarta ANTARA in English 0813 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0306133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, June 3 (ANTARA) -- PT Wijaya Karya [private 
company] and its brokering company PT Prima Comexindo signed a 
trade contract here Thursday with the Government of 
Turkmenistan, a member of the Commonwealth of Independent States 
(CIS), to supply the former Soviet republic with construction 
products. 
  During the signing ceremony, which was attended by visiting 
Turkmenistan President Saparmurad Niyazov, Indonesia's 
coordinating Minister for Political Affairs and Security Susilo 
Sudarman and Indonesia's Ambassador to CIS countries Rachmat 
Witular, the chamber of commerce and industry from both 
countries also signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) to 
encourage economic relations between their entrepreneurs. 
  In his welcoming speech, President Niyazov said that the MOU 
and the trade contract constitute the basis for closer bilateral 
economic cooperation as well as an official framework for 
business activities conducted by the two countries' 
entrepreneurs. 
  He also said that Indonesia may find it attractive to invest 
in the raw material processing industry now being developed in 
Turkmenistan. 
  Turkmenistan, he explained, has oil deposits of some 13 
trillion cubic metres but huge investments are needed for 
processing and transportation. 
  Niyazov also hoped that cooperation might be established 
with 
Indonesia in developing a textile industry in view of 
Turkmenistan's annual production of one million tons of cotton 
and Indonesia's established textile industry. 
  In the meantime, general chairman of Indonesia's Chamber of 
Commerce and Industry Aburizal Bakrie said that the newly signed 
MOU will provide opportunities to Indonesia's and Turkmenistan's 
businessmen to develop opportunities in trade, industry and 
investment. 
  President Director of PT Prima Comexindo Hashim S. 
Jojohadikusumo meanwhile said that bilateral economic relations 
have great potential given that, at 511 thousand tons annually, 
Indonesia is the world's largest cotton importer. 
  According to Jojohadikusumo, in addition to textiles, 
cooperation in investment and trade between Indonesia and 
Turkmenistan could also be established in cement, oil and gas. 
  He added that Indonesia will likely export frying oil, tea, 
aircrafts and railway coaches to Turkmenistan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

