<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   E. Timor Rebel Chief Discloses `Peace Plan' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    E. Timor Rebel Chief Discloses `Peace Plan' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0306140294 Quezon City Radio Filipinas in English 0230 GMT 
3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0306140294 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City Radio Filipinas </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The East Timor conference is now on its fourth day 
in Manila. In a video taped message to the delegates, Timorese 
rebel leader, Jose Ramos-Horta calls for negotiations to resolve 
the conflict in East Timor which Indonesia annexed in 1976. 
Horta was one of the foreign participants who were barred from 
entering the country. 
  The conference has been discussing alleged human rights 
violations in East Timor. During the conference the conveners 
also discussed the peace plan drafted by Horta and was earlier 
presented to the European Union in Brussels, Belgium in April 
1992. The peace plan states that the people of East Timor hope 
to build a society based on democracy and where the citizens are 
conscious of their responsibilities. 
  The peace plan also envisage three phases that should be 
undertaken upon withdrawal of Indonesian armed forces from East 
Timor. First, the first two years will be set for the holding 
of Indonesia-Portugal talks under the auspices of the United 
Nations Secretary General and with the participation of the East 
Timorese people. Phase two is anchored on a five-year 
transition stage in which East Timorese would govern themselves 
democratically through having their own local institutions. And 
phase three is defined as the stage of East Timor 
self-determination whereby the East Timorese may choose between 
free association or integration into Indonesia or independence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

