<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Assembly Proceedings Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Assembly Proceedings Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Election Law Considered </H4>

<F P=102> BK0306144894 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
0500 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0306144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Ninth National Assembly's Fifth Session enters 
its eighth work day today. In the morning plenary meeting, the 
National Assembly continued to discuss the revised draft law on 
elections of the People's Councils under the direction of 
National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc Manh. 
  The revised draft law includes a preamble and 71 articles in 
10 chapters. The draft law amends 54 articles, supplements 10 
others, and retains the other seven articles of the old law. 
  During their discussion, the deputies expressed their 
unanimous views on the quality of deputies specified by the 
revised draft law as persons who are loyal to the socialist 
Vietnamese fatherland, who can represent the people in various 
ways, who have records of good conduct and abide strictly by the 
law, who are enthusiastic in protecting the interests of the 
state and the people, who have good general backgrounds, are 
competent in carrying out National Assembly activities and 
resolving pressing local issues, and who are trusted by the 
people. 
  The deputies also discussed the composition of People's 
Councils and the quality of people's councilors. Some deputies 
suggested that candidates who failed in the first election 
should not be allowed to run in People's Councils by-elections, 
and that only new candidates should be allowed in such 
elections. Other deputies said that efforts should be made to 
ensure equality of rights between nominated candidates and 
independent candidates, and so forth. 
  This afternoon the National Assembly will continue its work 
at the conference hall in Hanoi. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27761 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas108_n_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Assembly Proceedings Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Assembly Proceedings Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    4 Jun Proceedings </H4>

<F P=102> BK0406135894 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1100 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0406135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Summary] "Dear friends: The Ninth National Assembly's 
fifth session entered its ninth day today. 
  "The National Assembly worked at the conference hall in the 
morning under the direction of National Assembly Vice Chairman 
Dang Quan Thuy. 
  "The deputies debated a revised draft law on the amendment 
of 
and supplement to a number of articles on the law on military 
service. There were 21 deputies airing their views. All those 
who spoke favored the idea of amending and supplementing the law 
on military service now in force. Most of them hailed the fact 
that the draft law had been supplemented with Articles 11, 9, 
23, 56, and 61 on the duty of economic organizations and of the 
administration to muster youths to comply with the law on 
military service. They pointed out the need to assign relevant 
economic organizations, public organs, and units with the duty 
of accepting their former personnel who have returned from 
military service. Many deputies asked that the law clearly 
specify that in cases where these organizations or organs are 
deactivated, the responsibility of arranging employment for 
these youths will rest with the War Invalids and Social Welfare 
Offices concerned." 
  Some deputies proposed that the law further specify the 
responsibility of People's Councils at various levels to 
supervise the enforcement of the law on military service. The 
question of temporary military deferment or temporary military 
exemption was also intensively discussed. 
  "The general views are that the law on military service has 
been carried out in a biased fashion, as there are fewer youths 
from wealthy families or whose fathers are party cadres and 
members carrying out military service than less-educated youths 
from poor families. It is precisely due to this that many 
deputies favor the idea of offering an appropriate benefit 
policy to those who have fulfilled their military service." 
  Some deputies urged the defense minister to reexamine the 
training program for two-year military draftees "as there have 
been complaints about military draftees having to spend more 
time on manual labor than on military training." 
  "Others proposed that members of Assault Youth Forces be 
exempted from military service." 
  This afternoon, the National Assembly deputies split up into 
groups for discussions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27762 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas108_n_94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

