<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Assembly Proceedings Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Assembly Proceedings Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Communique No. 8 Issued </H4>

<F P=102> BK0406080494 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1430 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0406080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Assembly Office issued Communique No. 8 
as follows: 
  Today, the National Assembly held a plenary meeting in the 
conference hall. In the morning, under the direction of 
National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc Manh, the National Assembly 
continued to debate the revised draft law on the organization of 
the people's councils and the people's committees and the 
revised draft law on the elections of delegates to the People's 
Councils. 
  Nine deputies, out of 41 deputies registered to address the 
meeting, expressed their views. They were Le Ngoc Sanh of Dac 
Lac, Tran Thi Le Thu of Binh Dinh, Ca Kha Sam of Son La, Lam 
Phuc Co of Yen Bai, Nong Thai Nghiep of Bac Thai, H' Nghia of 
Gia Lai, Pham Thi Son of Ba Ria-Vung Tau, Phan Tan Tai of Vinh 
Long, and Dieu Bao of Dong Nai. 
  Their opinions concentrated on the following issues: the 
number of annual meetings of the people's council; its 
supervisory role; the content of its supervisory role; the 
relationship between the people's council with the standing 
committee of the people's council and the people's committee; 
issues relating to organs responsible for the organization of 
elections; the application, selection, and introduction of 
candidates to the people's council; the election procedures; and 
the supplement of delegates to the people's council. 
  In the afternoon, under the direction of National Assembly 
Vice Chairman Nguyen Ha Phan, the National Assembly listened to 
a report on the draft law on the promotion of domestic 
investment presented by Minister Do Quoc Sam, chairman of the 
State Planning Committee. Then Nguyen Thanh Phong, vice chairman 
of the National Assembly's Economic and State Budget Committee, 
read an investigative report on the draft law on the promotion 
of domestic investment. National Defense Minister Doan Khue 
read a report on the revised draft law to amend and supplement 
some articles of the Law on Military Obligations. Then Pham 
Loi, vice chairman of the National Assembly's National Defense 
and Security Committee, read an investigative report on the 
revised draft law to amend and supplement some articles of the 
Law on Military Obligations. 
  Tomorrow, 4 June, in the morning, the National Assembly will 
meet in the conference hall and debate the revised draft law to 
amend and supplement some articles of the Law on Military 
Obligations. In the afternoon, the National Assembly deputies 
will exchange views in their delegations on the draft law on the 
promotion of domestic investment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

