<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Seek UNSC Warning to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Seek UNSC Warning to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0306112694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 3 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0306112694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A top Foreign Ministry official disclosed on 2 June 
that the government has decided that it will ask the UN Security 
Council [UNSC] to issue a warning to the DPRK (North Korea). 
The government decided that this is how it plans to deal with 
the issue of suspected development of nuclear weapons by North 
Korea in view of the Japan-U.S.-ROK meeting to be held in 
Washington on 4 June to discuss the issue. The same official 
indicated that the Washington meeting will be held so the three 
nations can act in concert, with an eye on the UNSC meeting. He 
also pointed out that two options were available -- a resolution 
to impose sanctions or a resolution of warning against North 
Korea. Considering that the PRC would have no choice but to 
veto a resolution for imposing sanctions, the official indicated 
the government plans to ask the UNSC to issue a warning against 
North Korea. 
  So far, the UNSC has twice adopted a presidential statement 
asking North Korea to follow IAEA regulations on inspection of 
its nuclear facilities. Although a warning is different from 
sanctions, it is expected that this will be a firmer action than 
a presidential statement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

