<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Information Council' To Focus on DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Information Council' To Focus on DPRK Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0406040894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Jun 94 
Evening Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0406040894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 2 June, a government source said that next week 
the government will hold a meeting of its informal consultative 
body, the "joint information council," on the alleged nuclear 
development by the DPRK (North Korea). The objective of the 
meeting is to discuss measures for coping with growing 
international tension over the North Korean issue. The North 
Korean situation has worsened since the UN Security Council's 
presidential statement urging North Korea's early acceptance of 
inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) -- 
made in response to the nation's attempt to hastily replace fuel 
rods used in its nuclear facilities. 
  The council was established in 1986 under the then Nakasone 
cabinet to reinforce the crisis management capability of the 
nation. The council is chaired by the (administrative) deputy 
chief cabinet secretary, and members include directors of the 
Foreign Ministry's International Information Bureau, the Defense 
Agency's Defense Policy Bureau, the National Police Agency's 
Security Bureau, the Cabinet Information Research Office, and 
the Cabinet Security Affairs Office, as well as the deputy 
director general of the Public Security Investigation Agency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

