<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kubo Says SDPJ Opposes Japan-U.S.-ROK Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kubo Says SDPJ Opposes Japan-U.S.-ROK Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0506131394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0506131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wataru Kubo, secretary general of the opposition 
Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], held a news conference 
at a hotel in Hachinohe City, Aomori Prefecture, on 4 June. 
During the news conference, he touched on the issue of imposing 
economic sanctions against North Korea for its suspected 
development of nuclear weapons and stated: "At a time when the 
United Nations has yet to make any decision, Japan, the United 
States, and South Korea must be cautious about the economic 
sanctions against North Korea. The SDPJ takes a position against 
the economic sanctions on North Korea." In this way, Kubo made 
it clear that the SDPJ will oppose any economic sanctions 
imposed by Japan, the United States, and South Korea against 
North Korea. During the news conference, Kubo also said that, 
through an SDPJ delegation which is scheduled to leave Japan for 
Pyongyang on 10 June, the party intends to urge North Korea to 
accept nuclear inspections by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] and hold dialogue with the United States and South 
Korea. 

</TEXT>

