<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MOPT Increases Foreign Exchange Services </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MOPT Increases Foreign Exchange Services </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0272A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 May 94 p 
7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0272A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Effective 1 July, the Ministry of Posts and 
Telecommunications [MOPT] will increase to 300 the number of 
post offices handling foreign exchange conversions, an increase 
of 40. The change represents one phase of the MOPT's 
globalization strategy and its aim is to boost customer services 
in competition with privately operated banks. The post offices 
providing the new services will convert currencies between the 
Japanese yen and seven other currencies, including U.S. dollar, 
French franc, and British pound; they are also scheduled to sell 
and cash travelers' checks in eight currencies, including the 
yen. 
  Based on a 12-region breakdown of the country, post offices 
newly designated to provide the money-conversion services 
include 10 each for Kanto and Tokyo, seven for Kinki, and six 
for Tokai, mostly in urban areas. Others included one each for 
Hokkaido, Tohoku, Shinetsu, Hokuriku, Chugoku, Shikoku, and 
Kyushu, and none for Okinawa. Sources at the International 
Operations Section of the Postal Savings Bureau explain, "These 
figures reflect the selection of post offices on the basis of 
the number of people who travel overseas, demand for currency 
conversion, and regional balance." 
  According to the MOPT, the majority of individuals who need 
to convert foreign currencies or to buy or cash travelers' 
checks are about 20 years old, but few of them have an occasion 
to use a post office. The goal for the increase in the number of 
post offices handling foreign exchange services is to boost the 
patronage of post offices by individuals in that age category. 
Privately operated banks doubled the number of bank branches 
offering such services on a nationwide basis to about 8,500 in 
the four-year period ending in 1992 and the MOPT decided to 
increase the number of post offices handling the services from a 
total of 100 three years ago. 
  The MOPT not only plans to increase the number of post 
offices offering foreign exchange conversion services, but to 
expand its international remittance services. 

</TEXT>

