<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Situation in North Korea Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Situation in North Korea Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    No Instructions Received on Sanctions </H4>

<F P=102> OW0606092894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0916 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0606092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 6 KYODO -- The Finance Ministry has not 
yet received any instructions over possible economic sanctions 
against North Korea, a senior ministry official said Monday. 
  But the ministry already has "know-how" to follow any U.N. 
Security Council resolutions on stopping bank remittance, as it 
did toward Iraq during the Persian Gulf war in 1990, Vice 
Finance Minister Jiro Saito told a regular news meeting. 
  Saito otherwise refused to comment, saying, "things have yet 
not progressed as far as imposing economic sanctions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27838 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas108_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Situation in North Korea Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Situation in North Korea Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on Sanctions </H4>

<F P=102> OW0306143594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1416 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0306143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 3 KYODO -- Japan, South Korea and the 
United States will seek sanctions against North Korea acceptable 
to China over Pyongyang's refusal of full inspection of its 
nuclear facilities, a senior Foreign Ministry official said 
Friday [3 June]. 
  "The United States feels it has been betrayed by North 
Korea," the official said. 
  Senior officials from the three countries will discuss 
slapping sanctions on North Korea in talks Friday and Saturday 
in Washington following Pyongyang's rejection of unimpeded 
inspections of its nuclear facilities. 
  Shunji Yanai, director general of the Foreign Ministry's 
Foreign Policy Bureau, will attend the meeting. 
  The Japanese Government confirmed Friday that it will 
firstly 
call on the U.N. Security Council to adopt a resolution blaming 
North Korea and if the United States proposes a resolution 
seeking economic sanctions against the North, Japan will agree 
to it, government sources said. 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa told a session of the House 
of 
Representatives Foreign Affairs Committee on Friday that without 
winning China's support the Security Council would not be able 
to exert any pressure on North Korea to accept the international 
call for inspections. 
  China is one of the five permanent Security Council members 
and if it exercises its veto power, can knock down any 
resolution. 
  A U.S. official said one main topic at the meeting will be 
Washington's request that Tokyo halt remittances to North Korea 
from pro-Pyongyang organizations and residents in Japan, which 
are believed to be a major source of Foreign Currency for the 
isolated, economically weak country. 
  If a veto by China prevents a possible U.S.-sponsored 
resolution from being adopted by the Security Council, the three 
nations are likely to impose their own sanctions against the 
North, the sources said. 
  In case the U.N. Security Council cannot reach agreement 
over 
the sanctions issue due to anticipated opposition from China, 
North Korea's traditional ally which favors a soft approach in 
the nuclear controversy, Japan would offer "maximum cooperation" 
in multilateral punitive measures, he said. 
  Japan could do its part by halting cash remittances to North 
Korea from pro-pyongyang organizations and residents in Japan 
and suspending trade with the communist country, Kakizawa said. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai reiterated Tokyo's 
concern over North Korea's defiance of the inspection demands. 
  "We are deeply concerned about this situation," Kumagai told 
a news conference. 
  "We would like to weigh what action to take in close concert 
with the countries involved, such as the United States, South 
Korea and China," he said. 
  Kumagai later said before a lower house panel, "we have no 
specific sanctions in mind. We will tenaciously try to 
persuade" North Korea to reach a negotiated settlement of the 
nuclear row. 
  On Thursday, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
informed the U.N. Security Council that Pyongyang's refusal to 
let inspectors conduct an unimpeded check of discharged fuel 
rods has made it impossible to verify whether plutonium has been 
diverted in the past to manufacture atomic bombs. 
  North Korea last month started to exchange without IAEA 
supervision the 8,000 fuel rods in its 5-megawatt reactor at 
Yongbyon, sparking another Security Council statement last week 
urging compliance with the agency's inspection demands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

