BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from the "NHK News 7" </F>
program] 
  [Text] The United States, Japan, and the ROK will start a 
trilateral meeting in Washington tonight, Japan time, to 
exchange views on the issue of the UN Security Council's 
economic sanctions against North Korea. In this regard, Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata, at a news conference held today at Aizu 
Wakamatsu City in Fukushima Prefecture where he is making a 
stump tour, touched on North Korea's suspected nuclear arms 
development and explained, without making a concrete reference 
to such measures as economic sanctions, the need to continue to 
carefully deal with the issue. 
  [Begin Hata recording] I hope from the bottom of my heart 
that North Korea will talk without reserve by candidly accepting 
the opinion of international society. Also, we need to do our 
best to seek understanding of North Korea. [end recording] 
  At the same time, Prime Minister Hata said that generally 
speaking, it is a matter of course for a nation to be able to 
deal with emergency situations. In this way, he generally 
admitted that the government is studying various possible 
measures Japan can take to deal with the situation. 
  On the other hand, Wataru Kubo, secretary general of the 
Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], held a news conference 
today in Hachinohe City in Aomori Prefecture. On how Japan 
should deal with the issue of North Korea's suspected nuclear 
arms development, he explained a negative view toward the idea 
of imposing sanctions against the DPRK by Japan, the United 
States, and the ROK. 
  [Begin Kubo recording] I think Japan, the United States, and 
South Korea must be cautious about the idea of imposing 
sanctions without any decisions by the United Nations. I think 
the SDPJ, for its part, will take a negative position on the 
idea. [end recording] 
  In making the remark, Secretary General Kubo indicated a 
negative view on the Japan-U.S.-ROK sanctions against North 
Korea. Moreover, he stated that the Japanese Government should 
do its utmost to solve the issue in an amicable way through 
dialogue. 
  With regard to the future domestic political situation, 
Secretary General Kubo stated that if a no-confidence motion in 
the Hata cabinet is approved, there will be no other option but 
for the cabinet to resign en masse. He thus reiterated the view 
that the Hata cabinet should voluntarily resign en masse after 
the fiscal 1994 national budget passes the Diet. 

</TEXT>

