Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Reports to Board of Governors 3 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Reports to Board of Governors 3 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0406005594 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2300 GMT 3 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0406005594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] 
stressed that a special inspection of two undeclared nuclear 
facilities is indispensable [pilsujok] to examine North Korea's 
diversion of nuclear material, and called for full-scale 
cooperation from North Korea. 
  Correspondent Cha Man-sun reports from Vienna: 
  [Begin Cha recording] Reporting on the status of the 
replacement of fuel rods to its Board of Governors during its 
informal meeting held yesterday [3 June] afternoon, the IAEA 
pointed out that the decisive opportunity [kyolchongjogin kihoe] 
to examine North Korea's diversion of nuclear material has 
already been lost. 
  The IAEA reported to its 35 Board of Governors member states 
that providing additional information, which has been demanded 
from early last year, and a special inspection of two undeclared 
facilities are indispensable for determining the exact amount of 
plutonium produced in North Korea. Thus, full-scale cooperation 
from North Korea is urgent. 
  At yesterday's Board of Governors meeting, Olli Heinonen, 
head of the inspection section who inspected the replacement of 
fuel rods in Yongbyon, stressed that because nearly all of the 
fuel rods were replaced in the portion where sample-taking is 
definitely required, the result of analysis cannot be trusted 
even if samples are taken. 
  Councilor Yun Ho-chin from the North Korean side and Kim 
Su-kil, researcher in the DPRK Foreign Ministry, who came from 
Pyongyang, attended the informal Board of Governors meeting 
yesterday. They repeatedly referred to North Korea's special 
position of withholding the withdrawal of Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty, and persistently refused interviews by 
reporters. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

