<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Consults With Other Nations on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Consults With Other Nations on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sanctions Discussed With U.S. </H4>

<F P=102> SK0406012694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2300 GMT 3 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0406012694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The ROK and the United States agreed to take gradual 
[tangyejogin] steps for sanctions against North Korea, which in 
the end refused the request of the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA]. 
  Correspondent Kim In-kyu reports from Washington: 
  [Begin Kim recording] Today at the U.S. State Department, 
Kim 
Sam-hun, ROK nuclear ambassador; and Robert Gallucci, U.S. 
assistant secretary of state, discussed appropriate 
countermeasures [taehung chochi] against the North Korean act of 
violating the Nuclear Safeguards Accord. They shared the view 
that they should take gradual sanctions against North Korea at 
the earliest possible date. 
  Following the talks between the ROK and the United States, 
Assistant Secretary Gallucci held a special briefing at the 
State Department and revealed that there was no difference in 
views whatsoever between the two countries on steps to be taken 
next, including sanctions against North Korea. 
  In particular, answering the question on a possibility of 
the 
beginning of actual sanctions against North Korea within this 
month, Assistant Secretary Gallucci said that for this issue, 
close consultations will be held with allied nations and with 
Standing Committee members of the UN Security Council between 
this weekend and next week. Thus, he made it clear that they 
will strongly push for sanctions this month. 
  Nuclear Ambassador Kim Sam-hun revealed that since the 
foundation for continuing dialogue with North Korea collapsed, 
steps for sanctions against North Korea were discussed with the 
United States and the UN Security Council. As a result, they 
unanimously expressed the position that a resolution for 
practical sanctions must be adopted before it is too late in a 
bid to not lose the momentum favorable to sanctions against 
North Korea. 
  Ambassador Kim Sam-hun and Assistant Secretary Gallucci 
pointed out that although a method of analyzing fuel rods among 
the three possible methods to determine the amount of plutonium 
North Korea has extracted up to now has vanished, another 
method, including a special inspection of a radiochemical waste 
dumping site, still remained. Thus, they suggested that there is 
room for dialogue if North Korea allows the special inspection. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

