<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition's Cooperation Asked </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition's Cooperation Asked </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0406061994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0601 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0406061994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 4 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam's 
government and the ruling Democratic Liberal Party asked the 
main opposition Democratic Party (DP) Saturday to go along with 
them on the North Korean nuclear dispute. 
  The Democratic Party, however, held an emergency meeting of 
its policy-making supreme council Saturday morning and adopted a 
resolution urging the government to work for peaceful resolution 
of the nuclear row through dialogue. 
  "Whatever happens on the peninsula, (we) have to prevent 
another war (in Korea)," the DP said in the resolution, asking 
the government to seek an independent method of settling the 
dispute through active contacts with North Korea. 
  Earlier, First State Minister for Political Affairs So 
Chung-won called DP Chairman Yi Ki-taek and stressed the need to 
form a united political front as the nuclear deadlock has 
reached a critical juncture. Since there would be many stages of 
economic sanctions against North Korea and Seoul does not yet 
know Washington's exact plans, confusion might arise if there is 
a split in the nation's stance on the issue, So said. 
  So promised Yi that the government will brief the opposition 
party on the North Korean problem when President Kim and Seoul's 
ambassador in charge of nuclear affairs, Kim Sang-hun, return 
home. So assured Yi that the government will try to reflect the 
opposition party's position when it works out concrete measures 
on North Korea. 
  The DP resolution also called on the United States and the 
United Nations to refrain from any provocative action and to 
help resolve the row through dialogue. 
  In addition, the Democratic Party asked North Korea to stop 
refueling at the 5-megawatt reactor immediately, and to allow 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to conduct special 
inspections of two unreported nuclear facilities. 
  The opposition party also demanded that Pyongyang guarantee 
the transparency of its nuclear program and scrap its decision 
to withdraw from the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty. 

</TEXT>

