<H3> <TI>   DPRK Expansion Plan Denounced </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Expansion Plan Denounced </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0406091394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0907 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0406091394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 4 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
Government on Saturday [4 June] denounced as "an extremely 
dangerous idea" the professed plan of North Korea to withdraw 
from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT) and expand 
nuclear activities. 
  North Korea said in a statement issued by Vice Foreign 
Minister Kang Sok-chu on Friday that they would push ahead with 
their withdrawal from the NPT and would expand "self-reliant 
nuclear energy industry" under the present manner. 
  "This is an extremely dangerous idea that makes a mockery of 
the hope of the international community and all the Korean 
people for the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula," the 
government said in a statement. 
  The statement released by Yi Song-kon, Seoul-side chairman 
of 
the South-North Joint Nuclear Control Commission, said the 
North's recent unilateral replacement of fuel rods at a 
5-megawatt atomic reactor was an act of fundamentally shattering 
the joint declaration of denuclearization. 
  "We in our part will continue to strive and take all 
available steps to strictly implement the denuclearization 
declaration under all circumstances," it said. 

</TEXT>

