<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Public Security Meeting Held </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Public Security Meeting Held </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0606032794 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0200 GMT 6 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0606032794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This morning, the government held a public-national 
security affairs-related ministers' meeting on North Korea's 
nuclear development. It decided to take all necessary 
countermeasures at home and abroad based on a firm policy to 
prevent by all means North Korea's nuclear development situation 
from causing public uncertainty or threatening the stability of 
the people's livelihood. 
  At today's meeting, presided over by Prime Minister Yi 
Yong-tok, the government analyzed North Korea's recent responses 
and military movements, checked our Armed Forces' preparedness 
and the government's readiness for an emergency, and discussed 
ways to consolidate a pangovernmental preparedness for national 
security by unifying the national view. 
  At today's meeting, the government decided to take all 
necessary countermeasures at home and abroad to prevent the 
situation which might cause public uncertainty or threaten the 
stability of people's livelihood in the midst of the rapidly 
developing situation, including the international community's 
move toward imposing sanctions against North Korea. 
  The government will also continue to maintain close 
cooperation with the United States for establishing a quick 
military preparedness in the event of an emergency, while 
increasing an all-time capability of gathering information by 
operating at full capacity the national security-related 
permanent consultative system between the ROK and the United 
States. In the meantime, the government will concentrate on 
making diplomatic efforts to see our position accomplished in 
the international community based on the successes of President 
Kim Yong-sam's diplomacy through his visits. 
  At the same time, the government will focus on establishing 
in-country public security by strongly dealing with, and taking 
legal measures against, those pro-communist forces that 
sympathize with or praise North Korea's allegations as seen at 
the ceremony launching the activities of the Korean Federation 
of General Student Councils [Hanchongnyon]. 

</TEXT>

