<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Situation in North Korea Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Situation in North Korea Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata: To Handle `Any' Contingency </H4>

<F P=102> OW0406115294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1142 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0406115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aizu-Wakamatsu, Fukushima Pref., June 4 KYODO -- 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata vowed Saturday to bolster Japan's 
preparedness to deal with any contingency that may derive from a 
standoff over the suspected North Korean nuclear arms program. 
  "Generally speaking, it is proper for a nation to arrange 
preparedness that would enable it to cope with any development," 
Hata said at a news conference. 
  Hata was speaking about Japan's response to a possible 
contingency on the Korean peninsula amid heightened tension from 
the announcement Friday by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) that it can no longer verify if Pyongyang diverted 
plutonium for nuclear arms production. 
  Hata earlier said Japan would join U.N.-led sanctions 
against 
North Korea if the Security Council voted to approve punitive 
steps, while making it clear that Japan would keep open the 
option of acting with the United States and South Korea in 
slapping sanctions even without such a U.N. decision. 
  The U.N. nuclear watchdog said Friday the North Korean 
discharge of spent fuel rods from a nuclear reactor has made it 
impossible to ascertain whether North Korea diverted plutonium 
from the reactor in the past. 
  "I am monitoring how North Korea would respond to a 
statement 
by the president of U.N. Security Council that urged it to 
comply with the safeguards measures demanded by the IAEA," Hata 
said. 
  "I want North Korea to accept international public opinion 
and open up their heart (to the inspection demand)," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27893 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas108_a_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' Say G-7 Agenda To Include DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Sources' Say G-7 Agenda To Include DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0506080094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0744 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0506080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 5 KYODO -- Topics on the agenda at the 
Group of Seven (G-7) summit of industrialized nations include 
situations in the former Yugoslavia and the Middle East, 
assistance needs of South Africa and Ukraine and the North 
Korean nuclear issue, government sources said Sunday. 
  Representatives of the G-7 nations -- Britain, Canada, 
France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States -- worked 
out an agenda of political dialogue for the July 8-10 meeting in 
Naples, Italy, the sources said. 
  Unlike previous G-7 summits, they said, the Naples summit 
will not issue a political declaration. 
  Instead, they will merely issue a chairman's declaration, in 
view of Russia's formal participation for the first time. 
  At previous summits, Kremlin leaders were invited to join 
their G-7 counterparts for a special session outside the 
framework of the actual summit. 
  Russia's participation in the G-7 discussion on the former 
Yugoslavia will be especially meaningful, considering the 
country's influence over fellow Slavs in Serbia. 
  The sources said Japan, which has not sent personnel to join 
the United Nations Protection Force (Unprofor) in the former 
Yugoslavia, will call for continued efforts to keep the conflict 
in Bosnia- Herzegovina from spreading. 
  Japan will convey its resolve to extend assistance to 
surrounding countries such as Macedonia to consolidate stability 
there, as well as post-conflict reconstruction assistance to 
other parts of the former Yugoslavia, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

