<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITJ To Offer International Video Data Services </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ITJ To Offer International Video Data Services </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0295A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 31 May 94 p 
11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0295A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] International Telecommunications of Japan (ITJ; Chuo 
ward, Tokyo; Hiroshi Ohara, president), a new international 
common carrier, will begin offering international video data 
transmission services within the year. It will aim to provide 
low-cost transmission services through the use of digital 
transmission using what is called the "C-band." In the past, 
international video data transmission was monopolized by Kokusai 
Denshin Denwa (KDD), but it appears that lower rates will go 
into effect with the participation of ITJ. 
  On the 30th, ITJ and Fuji Television conducted a joint 
experiment in transmitting digital data between Japan and the 
United States. A tracking and data relay system (TDRS) satellite 
and digital receiving facilities owned by Columbia 
Communications was used to transmit animated images from an 
Earth satellite station located in Washington State to Fuji 
Television headquarters in Shinjuku ward, Tokyo. 
  "C-band" operates at a frequency where attenuation 
distortion 
is minimal during rainfall. The recent experiment involved the 
use of the "Ku-band" because of the fear of jamming in the case 
of Earthbound radio waves in Japan, and demonstrated the 
commercial feasibility of receiving services. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

