<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MOPT Holds Hearings on Leased Telephone Lines </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MOPT Holds Hearings on Leased Telephone Lines </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0297A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 31 May 94 p 
5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0297A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] On 30 May, the Ministry of Posts and 
Telecommunications [MOPT] announced that it will hold hearings 
in the early part of next month, involving industry 
representatives, aimed at lifting the ban on "connections 
between dedicated circuits leased by businesses from Type I 
telecommunications operators such as Nippon Telegraph and 
Telephone (NTT) and urban public circuits operated by NTT. Such 
connections will have the impact of subleasing of so-called 
telephone circuits. Reductions in long-distance call rates and 
expansion of business opportunities can be expected on the one 
hand, while an adverse impact on NTT earnings can be expected on 
the other hand. The MOPT plans to use the hearings to determine 
the impact on NTT operations because of the proposed lifting of 
the existing ban and the necessary relief measures. 
  According to MOPT officials, if the ban is lifted on 
connections of public and dedicated circuits, "Theoretically, 
long-distance call rates should drop by about 30 percent." 
Currently, long-distance call rates using NTT's public and 
long-distance circuits are 180 yen for three minutes, while the 
same call using NTT public circuits and long-distance circuits 
owned by one of the new telegraph and telephone companies would 
be 120-140 yen. These rate reductions are expected to encourage 
growth in new ventures such as mail order businesses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

