<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Assembly Issues Communique No. 10 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Assembly Issues Communique No. 10 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0606154094 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1430 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0606154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Assembly Office issued Communique No. 
10, which indicated that this morning, the National Assembly 
deputies studied, exchanged views, and contributed views to a 
number of clauses and sections of the revised draft laws on the 
organization of people's councils and people's committees and on 
the election of people's councillors. 
  This afternoon, the National Assembly met in the conference 
hall under the direction of National Assembly Vice Chairman 
Nguyen Ha Phan to debate on the draft law on local investment 
promotion. 
  Altogether, 14 deputies aired their views. The deputies 
were: Le Xuan Tung of Hanoi, Tran Du Lich of Ho Chi Minh City, 
Nguyen Ngoc Tran of An Giang, Nguyen Dinh Giao of Quang Ninh, 
Hoang Minh Thang of Quang Nam-Da Nang, Phan Lam Phuong of Quang 
Binh, Lam Phung Vien of Soc Trang, Nguyen Duy Anh of Lam Dong, 
Nguyen Thu Ha of Thai Binh, Le Thi Thuy of Nghe An, Do Quoc Hung 
of Ba Ria-Vung Tau, Tran Chu Toan of Gia Lai, Nguyen Nhieu Coc 
of Hoa Binh, and Le Thi Thanh Liem of Ben Tre. 
  In expressing their views, the deputies concured with the 
names of the laws and with the necessity to promulgate them. 
They also maintained that once adopted by the National 
Assembly, the law on local investment promotion will create the 
legal basis and favorable conditions for the people to have a 
sense of security while investing in production and business 
operations, thus contributing to making the goal of making the 
people rich and the country powerful come true. 
  The deputies focused on key issues as follows: objectives 
and areas that need to be amended, role of state business 
establishments, measures to ensure and support investment, 
problems concerning the establishment of an investment support 
fund and investment credit gurantee, types of occupations and 
areas of activities that need investment privileges, and state 
management over investment promotion. 
  Tomorrow, 7 June, the National Assembly will continue to 
meet 
in the conference hall to debate the draft law on local 
investment promotion. 

</TEXT>

