<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Han Optimistic on PRC Taking Part in Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Han Optimistic on PRC Taking Part in Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0706021294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0153 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0706021294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New York, June 6 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu said Monday that China has shown a 
willingness to cooperate in international efforts to settle the 
North Korean nuclear problem and was unlikely to present an 
obstacle. 
  Han, visiting New York to clarify South Korea's position and 
cooperate with U.N. Security Council [UNSC] members on the 
nuclear problem, said there is no just cause for Chinese 
opposition to a U.N. resolution imposing sanctions on North 
Korea. 
  "Nobody can tell what China has in mind, but I think China 
does not have any just cause to oppose a U.N. resolution 
imposing sanctions on Pyongyang since North Korea is being 
uncooperative and there is no other way but to impose 
sanctions," Han said. 
  Han expected that a draft resolution would not be introduced 
at the Security Council in one or two days, saying, "a draft 
resolution has not been decided yet, and it should be decided 
through discussion among related nations." 
  The permanent UNSC members are in frequent contact on an 
unofficial basis because the North Korean nuclear problem is 
urgent, Han said. 
  "After having separate contacts with the ambassadors of the 
five permanent UNSC members and Japan, I have become aware that 
there is a consensus in the positions of South Korea, the United 
States and Japan and that the permanent UNSC members generally 
sympathize with the South Korean position," he said. 
  After holding talks with the ambassadors, Han met with 
Robert 
Gallucci, U.S. assistant secretary of State for political and 
military affairs, to reaffirm bilateral cooperation on the North 
Korean problem. 
  Han also met with Security Council President Salim Bin 
Mohammed Al Khussaiby and talked to U.N. Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali, who is visiting Europe. Han is scheduled 
to hold a press conference on Tuesday before returning home. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

