<DOCNO> FBIS4-27969 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas109_d_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-109 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Objectives for National Security Council Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Objectives for National Security Council Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0706020694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0144 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0706020694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 7 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam, 
after returning from visits to Russia and Uzbekistan, has called 
a National Security Council meeting for Wednesday [8 June], 
indicating his firm resolve to defend the country against 
possible provocation by a cornered North Korea. 
  The fact that a Security Council meeting has been called for 
the first time since the inauguration of the Kim administration 
in February 1993 underscores the gravity of the worsening North 
Korean nuclear row. 
  As stipulated by Provision 91 of the Constitution, the 
National Security Council is an official presidential organ from 
which the chief executive can seek advice on foreign, military 
and domestic affairs prior to deliberating policy at a cabinet 
meeting. 
  A National Security Council meeting is one notch higher than 
a meeting of national security-related ministers or a 
unification-security policy coordination meeting, convened 
frequently in the past to discuss the dispute over Pyongyang's 
nuclear program. 
  Consequently, it is designed to be called at a time of 
crisis 
and policy decisions forged at this kind of meeting carry much 
more weight, according to analysts. 
  While visiting Uzbekistan, President Kim said Monday, "North 
Korea's development of nuclear weapons is a problem on which not 
only the survival of the 70 million Korean people depends. It 
also threatens the peace and security of Northeast Asia as well 
as the world." 
  "We are keeping a close watch on North Korea 24 hours a day 
and our troops, the U.S. and U.N. forces have enough strength to 
deter a war on the Korean peninsula," Kim said. 
  This National Security Council meeting is a sizeable affair. 
It is being attended by the prime minister, deputy prime 
ministers, and the defense, foreign, home affairs and finance 
ministers in addition to the director of the Agency for National 
Security Planning. 
  The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, who is an 
associate member of the council, also has the right to speak at 
the meeting. 
  Chief and senior presidential secretaries can attend the 
meeting if the president so desires. It is understood that Kim 
has invited chief secretary Pak Kwan-yong, Yi Won-chong, senior 
presidential secretary for political affairs, Chong Chong-uk, 
senior secretary for foreign and National Security Affairs, Pak 
Chae-yun, senior secretary for economic affairs, and 
presidential spokesman Chu Ton-sik. 
  By presiding over the first meeting of the National Security 
Council, President Kim obviously wants to demonstrate both at 
home and abroad his determination to handle any developments 
arising from the North Korean nuclear dispute. 
  Officials at Chongwadae [presidential offices], however, 
took 
pains to stress that the meeting is being held in "a crisis 
situation." 
  The president and his top officials want to "check the 
possibility" of the North Korean question reaching the crisis 
point, they said. 
  President Kim appears to have considered three main 
objectives in calling the meeting. 
  First, Kim probably aims to demonstrate to the world that 
South Korea, as a nation that is most directly involved, is 
doing its utmost as the U.N. Security Council prepares to 
discuss sanctions against North Korea. 
  Second, the president wants to convey a strong message to 
North Korea not to misread the South's resolve and undertake any 
rash action. 
  And third, Kim intends to assure South Koreans that the 
nation's preparedness is complete and its surveillance 
water-tight, enabling them to depend on their government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

