<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Outcome of Cambodian Peace Talks Welcomed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Outcome of Cambodian Peace Talks Welcomed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0606115294 Manila BUSINESS WORLD in English 3 Jun 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> BK0606115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila BUSINESS WORLD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Philippine Government yesterday welcomed the 
results of the Cambodian peace talks which ended last 28 May in 
North Korea, the Department of Foreign Affairs [DFA] announced 
yesterday. 
  "The Philippines believes that the security of the region is 
based on the principles affirming the right of every state to an 
existence free of external interference and to determine its own 
future," DFA spokesperson Susan Castrense said. 
  During the peace talks, the Cambodian Government and the 
Khmer Rouge agreed to form a standing committee to begin meeting 
this 15 June so that issues dividing the two sides in Cambodia's 
civil war could be dealt with. 
  Foreign affairs officials pointed out the Philippines has 
played an active role in seeking a "comprehensive, fair, and 
reasonable political settlement" of the issue on Cambodia 
through the Association of Southeast Asian Nations. 
  It will be recalled that Manila dispatched 702 security 
personnel to Cambodia as part of its contribution to the United 
Nations Transitional Authority in Cambodia after the 
UN-sponsored Paris Agreement was signed in December 1991. 
  On the level of ASEAN, the Philippines participated in the 
Asia-Japan Tripartite Cooperation in Cambodia in response to an 
invitation made by the Japanese Government. Manila also 
contributed $100,000 to the UN Trust Fund for the Cambodian 
peace process in response to an appeal made by UN Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali. 
  The Philippines recognized Kampuchea in April 1976 as the 
legitimate representative of the Kampuchean people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

