<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK `Warning' About Next Nuclear Stage </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK `Warning' About Next Nuclear Stage </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0606231694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2100 GMT 6 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0606231694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cha Man-sun from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] Last night, North Korea sent an urgent message to 
the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA], warning that it 
would have no choice but to turn its peaceful nuclear activities 
to the next stage if the IAEA refers its nuclear issue to the UN 
Security Council or continues to apply pressure. 
  (Pak Yong-nam), director of North Korea's Atomic Energy 
General Department, sent a message to IAEA Director General Hans 
Blix last night in which he said it was an unjust act to North 
Korea for the IAEA to reach the hasty conclusion that it would 
be impossible to analyze samples from nuclear fuel rods because 
it was still possible. 
  It is analyzed that North Korea sent such a message as a 
part 
of its diplomatic strategy aimed at lessening the pressure on 
it. In the event that the IAEA Board of Governors takes a 
hard-line measure against North Korea, it seems possible that 
North Korea will take some tough measures, including its 
withdrawal from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. 
  The IAEA Board of Governors will map out countermeasures 
tomorrow afternoon after discussing the issue of North Korea's 
violation of the nuclear agreement as an isolated agenda item. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

