Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Vows To Support Resolution on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Vows To Support Resolution on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0606153494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1523 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0606153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 7 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
vowed Monday night that Japan will make every effort within the 
limits of its Constitution to cooperate in the event the U.N. 
Security Council [UNSC] imposes sanctions on North Korea over 
its alleged nuclear arms development program, a senior Foreign 
Ministry official said. 
  Hata made the remarks at an emergency meeting convened 
following weekend consultations of Japan, the United States and 
South Korea in Washington to discuss the North Korean nuclear 
issue, the official said. 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa, Chief Cabinet Minister 
Hiroshi Kumagai, Vice Foreign Minister Kunihiko Saito and Shunji 
Yanai, director general of the Foreign Ministry's Foreign Policy 
Bureau who attended the Washington get-together -- were present 
at the meeting Monday. Hata told the meeting that if the 
Security Council decides to take measures, including sanctions, 
to put pressure on North Korea to change its position, Japan 
will support the move and cooperate as much as possible within 
the framework of the Constitution, the official said. Hata also 
instructed the government to study measures the country would 
take in case the Security Council adopts the resolution. 
  Hata strongly urged North Korea to fully cooperate with the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to eliminate 
international suspicions that it is developing nuclear weapons. 
He said Japan will make every diplomatic effort to solve the 
problem peacefully, through international coordination, the 
official said. The diplomatic efforts include close 
consultations with South Korea, China and other relative 
countries, the official said. 
  In a related development earlier in the day, government 
officials indicated Kakizawa may visit Seoul as early as this 
weekend to hold talks with his South Korean counterpart Han 
Song-chu. The date of the foreign ministerial meeting, however, 
has not yet been decided due to the Diet schedule. Kakizawa may 
also visit China, according to government sources. 
  Yanai, U.S. Assistant secretary of State Robert Gallucci and 
Kim Sam-hun, South Korea's special envoy on the nuclear issue, 
agreed over the weekend to adopt a united front on the North 
Korean nuclear issue. In a joint statement issued after the 
talks, the three nations called on the United Nations to take 
prompt action against Pyongyang, including the consideration of 
sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

