<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Plans To Visit ROK `Soon' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Plans To Visit ROK `Soon' </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on Expected Visit </H4>

<F P=102> OW0606112094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1108 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0606112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 6 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa will leave for South Korea next Saturday [11 June] for 
bilateral talks expected to focus on the North Korean nuclear 
issue, government sources said Monday. 
  The move follows Saturday's talks in Washington between 
high-level officials of Japan, South Korea and the United 
States, where it was decided to urge the U.N. Security Council 
to consider possible sanctions against North Korea. 
  The sources said Kakizawa and South Korean Foreign Minister 
Han Sung-chu would meet next weekend to discuss the prospect of 
Security Council sanctions and of unilateral sanctions by the 
three countries if the council fails to act. 
  Vice Foreign Minister Kunihiko Saito told a press conference 
earlier in the day that Japan wants to hold the foreign 
ministerial meeting as early as possible, considering the 
heightened tension relating to the issue of North Korea's 
alleged nuclear weapons development program. 
  But he said Kakizawa and Han would be discussing a wide 
range 
of issues, in what will constitute a regular foreign ministerial 
meeting. 
  The previous such meeting was held in September, when Han 
visited Japan. 
  Meanwhile, Kakizawa, Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata and Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai were scheduled to meet Monday 
night to listen to a report from Shunji Yanai, director general 
of the Foreign Ministry's Foreign Policy Bureau, who represented 
Japan at last weekend's trilateral talks. 

</TEXT>

