<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. `Not Considering' Action Against DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. `Not Considering' Action Against DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0606044194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0429 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0606044194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 6 KYODO -- Washington is not 
considering military options against North Korea for its refusal 
to allow checks of its nuclear facilities and will work through 
the United Nations, a senior Foreign Ministry official said 
Monday [6 Jun]. 
  Yutaka Kawashima, director general of the Foreign Ministry's 
Asian Affairs Bureau, was responding to concerns posed at a 
House of Representatives Budget Committee hearing that the 
United States was considering independent sanctions. 
  "The concern of the U.S. Government has been squeezed down 
to 
how to respond through the UN Security Council and there was no 
thinking about military options," Kawashima said in response to 
a question. 
  Kazuo Kitagawa, a member of coalition component Komeito, had 
asked Kawashima about remarks made by U.S. Secretary of Defense 
William Perry in a U.S. television interview that it is possible 
that independent sanctions may be imposed on North Korea by 
countries involved in the issue. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata said that Japan will provide its 
efforts through a number of routes, while noting that Tokyo is 
seeking a negotiated resolution to North Korea's refusal to open 
its nuclear activities to full international inspections. 
  Hata, speaking at the same committee sesssion, said Japan 
will cooperate with the international community "within the 
limits permitted by the constitution" if the UN should decide to 
impose sanctions on North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

