<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Chief Backs Call for Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Keidanren Chief Backs Call for Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706043994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0417 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706043994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 7 KYODO -- U.S. Undersecretary of 
Commerce for International Trade, Jeffrey Garten, urged industry 
deregulations during talks with a Japanese business leader on 
his visit to Japan on Tuesday. 
  Garten told Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman of the Federation of 
Economic Organizations (Keidanren), that the United States would 
like to know how it can help Japan's deregulation. 
  He noted that numerous proposals are being made in Japan's 
industry, but that it is doubtful that they will actually be put 
into action. 
  In response Toyoda expressed enthusiasm for deregulatory 
measures, saying, "We must go forth with deregulation even if it 
hurts." He said he hoped the U.S. Government would let it be 
widely known that deregulation will lead to more business 
opportunities. 
  Toyoda also said that he is pressing the government to set 
up 
a surveillance body to oversee deregulation. 
  On the Japan-U.S. framework trade talks, Garten said he 
expects it will take some time before the discussions make 
progress. 
  The U.S. official implied that the Japanese Government 
should 
continue making income tax cuts, pointing out that fiscal 
measures taken so far are insufficient to encourage domestic 
demand. 
07 JUN 0446 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

