<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Pledges To `Root Out' Corruption </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Pledges To `Root Out' Corruption </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0606045394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0437 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0606045394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 6 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
pledged Monday [6 Jun] to root out corruption related to public 
construction works by replacing the traditional designated 
bidding system with an open bidding system. 
  "Public construction works must have trustworthiness and 
transparency," said Hata, answering questions at the House of 
Representatives Budget Committee. "Successive scandals were 
regrettable." 
  "We are taking measures such as a full-fledged introduction 
of the competitive bidding system. We will constantly carry out 
the measures in order to get rid of bid-rigging and other unjust 
practices," he said. 
  In April, prosecutors announced the end of 13 months of 
investigations into a series of bribery scandals involving 
politicians and major construction firms. 
  A total of 32 people -- including a Diet legislator, two 
governors, two mayors and officials of eight major construction 
companies and a large paper manufacturer -- were indicted as a 
result of the investigation. 

</TEXT>

