Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii: Economy `Heading in a Better Direction' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fujii: Economy `Heading in a Better Direction' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706021694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0210 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706021694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 7 KYODO -- The Japanese economy is 
heading in a better direction with "slight changes in nuance" 
evident in assessments of its performance, Finance Minister 
Hirohisa Fujii said Tuesday [7 Jun]. 
  Industrial output is near to bottoming out and inventory 
adjustments are also improving, Fujii told a news conference 
after a morning cabinet meeting. 
  Fujii had been saying that the economy is mixed with good 
and 
bad signs and that experts were split in their assessments. 
  The cabinet adopted a monthly economic report at the morning 
meeting. 
  The June report prepared by the Economic Planning Agency 
stressed emergence of improving areas in the still-sluggish 
economy. The previous report had emphasized the sluggishness of 
the economy although noting some signs of improvement. 
  Fujii also said that international organizations are 
forecasting a recovery in the second half of 1994 for the 
Japanese economy in their latest economy reports. 
  He particularly cited reports by the Organization for 
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) on Monday and by the 
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in April. 
  The two institutions said in separate reports that the 
Japanese economy will pick up in the second half from sluggish 
growth in the first half to post a real 2 percent growth in 1994 
before staging a full recovery in 1995. 
  To back up the improving outlook at home and abroad at "this 
delicate time," Fujii stressed the importance of steadily 
implementing the fiscal 1994 budget and the government's record 
15.25 trillion yen stimulus package launched in February. 
  The long-delayed budget for the current year that started 
April 1 is expected to pass the House of Representatives on 
Wednesday, with deliberations in the House of Councillors to 
begin the same day. The government is now running under a 
provisional budget. 
  Turning to the issue of possible economic sanctions against 
North Korea, Fujii said it all depends on the UN Security 
Council. 
  He cited the move to stop bank remittances to Iraq during 
the 
Persian Gulf War in 1990 as an example of the Finance Ministry's 
experience in complying with UN resolutions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

